{"/service/ndnp/deu/batch_deu_jessicajones_ver01/data/sn87062237/00383342855/1921012801/0028.xml":{"full_text":"8Y THE CHAMBER OF\nYear's Work Reviewed by the\nOfficers at the Annual\nMeeting.\nPROGRAM ALSO SUGGESTED\nMuch was accomplished by the Cham\nber of Commerce in the year 1920, aoeording\nt.> the report of the officers, which was\nrend nt the annual meeting in the Hotel\n<'n Pont last night. This rcyiort, presented\n1 y President Alfred D. W arner, Jr., and\nSecretary William T. Budd, set forth the\nf illowing accomplishments during the\nyear:\nThe securing of the passage of the act\nauthorising tno Levy Court to issue\nbonds for the purpose of remodeling the\nold 15. A O R. R. bridge, now known as\nthe Augustine Bridge, and making it\navailable for pedestrian and vehicular\ntrr'lic: the sale of these bonds at par,\nthrough the efforts of your committee.\nThe assistance given in solving the\nproblem which confronted the Council\nof Wilmington at the tune of the contre\nregarding the renewal of the ccn\n>rk of the conservation and\nfiro prevention committee in its\ncampaign for the prevention of fire losses.\nand the development of a rapidly-frow\ning public sentiment demanding a fire\nmarshal and a modern, full-paid fire\ndepartment for (his city.\nSecuring the location in Wilmington\nof a large sugar refining plant, now in\ncourse of develop ment end construction.\nThe assistance given in promoting and\norganizing (he Tr smers Aid Society by\narranging meetings addressed by Thoms\u00ab\nMott Osborne and Dr. George W. Kirch\nwav.\ngiven (hie Ptat* Board\n<f Health b> s\u00ab -ruling,through our mem\nh r<. the suni >921 to ena ble the Bureau\nf Venereal Dim* \u00abe Control to continue\ntl. wi-rk f stumping nt this disease in\ntin\u00ab citv.\nversv\ntracts for fire service.\nThe wi\nSecured contributions of fS,760\u2014thanks\nto the ceueruffity of <mr members.\u2014for\nthe fund for the erection in Washington\nof a permanent headquarters for the\nChamber of C< ir.merce f the t'nited\nStates, \"ThcH< ir.cef American Buainces.\"\nThis sun', includes the contribution of\nthis organization.\nTbo\n:s(\nH VUBOll DTVELOrM! NT.\nTfie development ->f mir harbor and\nthe con\u00ab: netion of deep-sea terminal\nfur coastwise and fore g;/ commerce is a\nP eject lone advocated 7 by your organ\nit; >n, and wo are pleased to report that\npl ins are now in course of preparation,\nand the Board of Harbor Commissioners\nexpect to ask for bids for the actual con\nst'action of the work in tlie early spring.\nThe co-ope-ation of (he Federal gov\nernment in this work, by straightening,\nwidening and deepening the lower\nstretches of the Christiant river is being\nsought, and surveys and estimates of\ncosts have been ordered. The en ti \u00abmatter\ni\u00ab in a very satisfactory state of progress.\nThe new municipal produce whan has\nbeen completed and is in use.\nHOUSING.\nWhile tiie housing situation is not as\nacute at this t ime as it was a year ago, the\ncondition is still far from satisfactory.\nRents are high and houses scarce, and j\nw;th the return of prosperity we will be\nin reed of raanv additional houses. It,\ns ho]>ed that with the return of normal\ne many new house\u00ab will be built, and J\ntrat the problem of adequately housing\nour ever-increasing population will be\nmet.\nINDUSTRIAL BUILDINGS. FACTORIES AND\nWAREHOUSES.\nWhile the demand for industrial build\nir.srs, factories and warehouses has not\nbeen as great as it was in the year pre\nvious there still is a considerable number\nof inquiries, and with the general revival\ncf 1 usiness through; ut the country, which\nwe hope will be in the near future, the\ndemand undoubtedly will greatly in\ncrease.\nDuring the year your officer' co-oper-\nr.'ed and assisted in the following cam- j\npaigns Thrift week, Balvati\nService Fund. Community\nground Fund, Mayor\"' Housing Com- j\nmit tee. Committee on Wilmington Trade\nSfbool, Fire Prevention Week, Hoover\nRelief C\nGathered Rtat:s*ics for the United\nStates er guie- r s office in connection with j\nthe commerce of Wilmington harbor.\nConferred with the Levy Court in re- j\n:ion to the needs for new bridges across\nthe Brandywine river.\n.Arranged, in co-operation with the\nKiwanis and Rotary Clubs, a dinner to\nthe newly-naturalized American citizens.\nAssisted the Department of Commerce,\nWashington, in connection with the census\nof manufactures.\n:on A-my Home j\nService Plav\npRign\n1:\nCONVENTION^.\nYour organization, ro-operating with\nthe alumni of the University of Peansyl\nvi nia. extended invitations to inen\u00f9b\u00ear\u00eei\nthat organisation to visit Wilmington\nce the occasion of the fifth conference of\ni \\ssociated Pennsylvania Clulie. which\n1 Id a highly successful meeting ir, this\nc y on February 18, 19, 1920\nVi e invited ihe Peninsula Horticultural\nSociety to bold its 1920 convention and\nexhibit in this city, and co-operated with\na: cj assisted its officers ir. making th\u00bb*\naffair one of the most pleasant and\nc- ul it ever has held.\n't our organization wrta represented bv\nde legation\u00ab to the following conventions I.\nad e -nferer.ccs during the year: Annual\nmeeting of tn C hamber of Commerce of\n\nKUC\nt.>** United Sf.'.tes; annua! meeting of the\nvincncan Academy of Political and Social\nScience; sunnier in\u00bb-\u00ab*ting of the National\nIndustrial Traffic League; various rncet\nmgK of the Delaware State Bankern As\nsociation;\nAtlantic Deeper Waterways Association;\nannual meeting of the National Rivers\nHt.d Haroors Congress; hearings before\ngovernment engineers relative to Chesa\n<k Delaware canal m ^rovemente;\n'\u00bbeating the necessity of prorapt.lv\nbudding si ship canal across the State of\nN'-w Jersey; the resurvey and improve\nment of the Christiana river in con\nr.* -don with the local harbor project,\ni\u00bb Four Referendums, involving 25 ques\nt or.s relating to national policies sub\nmilted bv the Chamber of Commerce of\nthe 1 nited States, and pertaining to the\nfollowing subjects, wore acted upon:\nCreation of ft Department of Public\nWork\u00bb; employment relations -industrial\nemployment relations public utilities;\nPublic' utilities.\nContributed \u00ce 1,000 toward the estab- j\nloth ment of the Wilmington Trade School. 1\nRecommended that the Litem t\u00e4te Com-\nmeree Committee enable the railroads to\nre-establish their credits and place them\nin n position to render ad\u00e9quat* service\nto the shippers and the public by author\nize, g an increase in freight rates.\nRecommended increased salarie\u00ab and j\ntne Retirement feature for civilian\ng neers in the employ of the War Depart\nifieht\nUrged the I^evy Court to expedite the\nwork on the Lincoln Highway feeder be\ntween this city and Newark, Delaware\nRecommended universal military train\nannual\nconvention of the\nj\n1\n\nen-\ning of the vouth of the country between\nj the ages of 18 and 21 by appropriate le*'\n1 lation bv Congress, in order to establish\nl a sound military policy, with suitable\nj educational, vocational and physical train\ning. instruction and the Am\u00e9ricanisa\ntion of such of our youth as needed, aamef\ni and the inculcation of a high sense 0.\ncivic responsibility in our young people\nConsidered and made recommendations\nrelative to sundry bills ponding before the\nGeneral Assembly of Delaware at the\nspecial session of 1920.\nCondemned the action of those men\nwho brought about the railroad strike in\nApril, and approved the fidelity of those\nemployes who remained faithful to their\ndutv, and the leaders of the railroad\nBrotherhoods in trying to restrain their\nmembers from striking\nApproved and urged the passage of the\nPoindexter Bill (X. B. 4204) providing\nfew punishment for obstructing or delay\ning interstate or foreign commerce.\nIndorsed the plan of the Savings Divi\nsion of the United States Treasury.\nApproved safeguarding the rights and\nprivileges of the individual.\nOpposed permitting any organisation\nor association to exorcise a power of con\ntrol over its members in violation of their\nrights or liberties as sought to be safe\nguarded under the Constitution of the\nUnited States.\nDemanded the repeal of all acts con\nupon special classes,\noases of citizens equal\nis\n\nact prescribe that aD combinations in\nicstraint of trade which are injurious to\nthe public good be declared unlawful.\nThat the rights of individuals be res\n1 pected and that every organisation make\nitself financially responsible for the acts\nof its officers, agents and members, and\ni that it be made legally and actually lin\nswerablo for all injury caused; supported\nthe Davev Sedition Bill; supported and\nurged the adoption of the \"waterways\nplank\" in the platforms of the several\npolitical parties; considered the need and\ndesirability of a municipal hospital\nMade efforts through U R Senator L\nHeister Ball to assist the Pusey A Jones\nCo., to obtain relief from the Emergency\nFleet Corporation, whereby a sale of tiie j\nplant mignt bo effected and the busitess\nof the company continued. (This matter\nnow is in the court\u00ab).\nRecommended that (ho Publie Utility\nCommission grant to the Diamond State\nTelephone Co. authority to chargn such\na rat\u00ab as would enable it to continue and\nto improve upon its present servioo, and j\nto derive a fair return upon it* invest\nmont, said rate to he determined by the\ncommission after careful investigation\nof the data before it.\nBent on record with the International\nJoint Commission opposing the canal\niaation of the St. Lawrence river.\nApproved the movement and accepted\nthe invitation of the Rotary Club to ap\npoint memWr? to a general City Com\nmittee to consider new charter for the\nforring privileges\nthus making all el\nin fact before the law\nDemanded that the Federal anti-trust\ncit\nAmended\nand brought up to date the\nby-lawp, the chief feature being the giving\nto the several sections a wider control\nof tbeir activities\nCreated two new- Sections; Automobile\nTrades and Wholesale Sections.\nUrg\u00bbd that the Federal government\nfind means to provide funds on\u00bb] to p*y to\nthe railroads the monies due them, there,\nby enabling the ronde to place orders for\nThey WORK\nwhile you sleep*\nI\nTake one or two Cascarets occasionally\nto keep \\our liver and bowels active\nWhen biho\ntlrung or for a coid, upset stomach or\noad breath, nothing acts so nicely a.\u00ab\nliscarets Children love them, too 10\n26, 50 cent*\nus, eonsripated, headachy, un-.\n*r*\n\nc\nI Used Cars\nj\nHave you over eunsidered the\nj advantages of purchasing a good\nused car'\nNot only the economy\u2014-but the\nsatisfaction <\u00abf owning a oar which\nbelongs to a higher class of mechani\ncal excellence tlian any new car you\nobtain at the \u00ab\u00e2me price\nSee those car\u00bb\u2014and let us demon\netrate the ones that appeal to you\nRepriced\nPACKARD\u20143-3o \u00ce win-Sii, Dem\nonstrator. A 7-pasflcnger Tour\ning Car in excellent condition\nRBO\u2014Ru nabout.\nPAIGE\u2014Touring \u00abjumped with\nwinter top.\nPACKARD--\u2014 1-\u00d68 Twin-Six Tour\ning at a price within the aoop* of\nthe moderate buyer Time pay\nmeats if desired\nFRANKLIN\u2014 \u00dcA Coup\u00ab.\nTime payment\u00ab if desired.\nPackard Hstor Car Co.\nOf Philadelphia\n411 Orange St., Wilmington\nequipment \u00ab.rd \u00abupplien, and facilitate (be\nimproromnnt of general btunwwa con\nth _. fh thm\nstWi^ss \u00c4\u00abt\nOfwmxt\u0153 by neHirg the atiefltion of\nour mAm'ffictUTera to the servi on that\n\"\u00ee.fc\u00c2r 1 s.^\" b 3; *rs\nA*\u00ef\u00ee'^i r .*w U ,or\na t Aw,onat,tm\niftjP\u00eetf\nBo2d \u00c4! \u00d45\n^uZri*n 0 fil!-H.i r 'ri2^! T T*a:^ /.\u201ej\nn\u00dcn m T^T m '8k e^^bod\nnr.i\u00eev\nto MiuIn\nnrJviSaf^l n\u00dcSiihTpl^ i n v2?fw. It!\n|Wldefor^yligb\u00ab Raving in the Worn\njind\nApproved combining Armisti\nlankagiving Day*.\nco\nTh\nCORSJBRV4TIOS ANT) ntlB PRBVBNf IO